## [SECTION 1 — 0:00 to 1:00] The problem

*[Screen: terminal, project folder visible, nothing running yet]*

> "Seventy percent of researchers say they've failed to reproduce another scientist's computational experiment. Not because the science was wrong — often because the code had a hardcoded path on someone's laptop, or the software versions weren't recorded, or the data was never shared. The estimated cost globally is around two hundred billion dollars a year in wasted research.
>
> ValiChord is infrastructure designed to fix this. Not a checklist, not a badge scheme — actual distributed infrastructure where independent validators cryptographically verify that a published computational study reproduces, and the result is recorded permanently.
>
> What I'm going to show you now is the core of the system: four separate peer-to-peer networks written in Rust, running as real independent processes on this machine, executing the full validation protocol. This is not a simulation or a mockup. These are real Holochain nodes — the same technology that would run on a validator's laptop in Cardiff or Cape Town — talking to each other over a real distributed network, right here."

