## [SECTION 4 — 3:00 to 5:30] The commit-reveal protocol — the core

*[Screen: test name appears — `2. Full commit-reveal round > two validators commit, phase opens, both reveal`]*

> "This is the most important test in the suite. I want to explain what's about to happen.
>
> The central problem with any reproducibility system is gaming. If validators can see the researcher's claimed results before submitting their own findings, they might — consciously or not — anchor on those numbers. And if the researcher can see what validators found before revealing their own claimed results, they could adjust what they say they expected.
>
> ValiChord uses a blind commit-reveal protocol that makes both of these things cryptographically impossible.
>
> Watch what happens."

*[Screen: two sets of "Conductor ready" messages appear — two nodes starting]*

> "Two independent validator nodes just started. They cannot see each other's data. Each is running in a completely isolated process with its own cryptographic keys."

*[Screen: more conductor output, long pause while the test runs]*

> "Right now, the test is executing the protocol step by step. Each validator is sealing their assessment — generating a random nonce, computing a cryptographic hash of their findings, and publishing only that hash to the shared network. Their actual findings stay private on their own node.
>
> The researcher also sealed their claimed results before the validators even started — that commitment hash is already on the network. Neither party can change what they've committed to.
>
> When both validator hashes are recorded, the network automatically transitions to the reveal phase. Both validators then publish their full assessments. The system verifies on-chain that each revealed assessment matches its earlier hash. If the hashes don't match — if someone tried to change their findings after seeing the other side — the reveal is rejected.
>
> This test confirms the complete protocol runs end to end across both nodes."

